# Windows shell execution (agents)

Cursor on this machine may run **PowerShell** even when commands look like bash. Repo root: `C:\Projects\solar` (Git Bash: `/c/Projects/solar`).

## When to use which approach

- **Simple Docker Compose** (no pipes, no `$()`, no HEREDOC): set Shell tool `working_directory` to `C:\Projects\solar` and run `docker compose …` directly.
- **Everything else** (pipes, `head`/`grep`, `$(pwd)`, `scripts/*.sh`, git HEREDOC, `source .venv/bin/activate`): wrap in `bash -lc '…'`.

## Path rules

| Context | Format | Example |
|---------|--------|---------|
| Shell tool `working_directory` | Windows backslashes OK | `C:\Projects\solar` |
| Docker `-v` from PowerShell | Git Bash / Docker Desktop style | `"/c/Projects/solar/frontend:/ui"` |
| Inside WSL bash (`bash -lc`) | WSL mount path | `/mnt/c/Projects/solar` |
| Inside Git Bash | MSYS path | `/c/Projects/solar` or `c:/Projects/solar` |

Never use `C:\…` backslashes inside Docker volume strings.

`$(pwd)` and repo scripts must run inside bash, not bare PowerShell. When `bash -lc` lands in WSL, `cd` to `/mnt/c/Projects/solar` (or rely on `working_directory` and skip `cd`).

## Repo-canonical commands

From repo root (`working_directory` or `cd "c:/Projects/solar" &&`):

```bash
docker compose run --rm test
docker compose run --rm frontend-test
```

One-off container with bind mount:

```bash
docker run --rm -v "/c/Projects/solar:/repo" -w /repo python:3.14-slim-trixie \
  python scripts/sync-version.py --check
```

Repo scripts (always via bash):

```bash
bash scripts/check-python.sh
bash scripts/reset-local-password.sh
```

See `python.mdc` for Docker-first Python/pytest policy.

## Anti-patterns

| Avoid (PowerShell) | Use instead |
|--------------------|-------------|
| `Select-Object -First N` | `bash -lc '… \| head -n N'` |
| `Select-String -Pattern` | `bash -lc '… \| grep pattern'` |
| `$env:VAR` / backtick continuations | `export VAR=…` inside `bash -lc` |
| `cat <<'EOF'` for git commits | Full commit wrapped in `bash -lc '…'` |
| `C:\Projects\…` in `docker -v` | `"/c/Projects/…"` |

## On failure

Retry once with `bash -lc` and POSIX paths before changing command logic or abandoning the approach.
